The Telegraph - Calcutta : Sports

 Jayasuriya set for century

Colombo: Sri Lanka are determined to cap star batsman Sanath Jayasuriyas special 100 th Test with a series clinching victory in the second and final Test against Bangladesh starting here. 

The hosts are leading 1-0 after winning the opening Test by an innings and 96 runs. 

Jayasuriya, set to become the first Sri Lankan to figure in 100 Tests, was lavishly praised for his form and fitness by coach Tom Moody on the eve of the match. 

Sanath has worked hard to remain fit and in good touch for so many years, Moody said. The way he trains is an example for any cricketer and professional. The whole squad is happy for him. It is great for him and great for Sri Lankan cricket. 

Jayasuriya, who made his Test debut against New Zealand in 1991, has so far scored 6,567 runs in 99 matches with 14 centuries. 

He is also the fourth batsman after Sachin Tendulkar, Sourav Ganguly and Inzamam-ul Haq to complete 10,000 runs in one-day cricket. 

Moody said it was vital for his team to finish the series against Bangladesh with a victory. (AFP) 




